            </div>
            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology">East (Mashreq) &gt; Levant &gt; Lebanon &gt; Beqaa</p>
               <p>rural sedentary dialect</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p>The name is believed to be a reference to the landslides that sometimes occur in 
                   the region. Zahle is the capital of the Beqaa district and lies at the eastern 
                   foot of the Lebanon mountains. The climate is hot in summer and cold to very cold 
                   in winter, due to its location at 1000m above sea level and being cut off from the 
                   milder Mediterranean climate by the mountains.</p>
               <p>It is most famous for its kitchen as well as for its wine and <hi rendition="#i">ˁaraq</hi> 
                   production. It is predominantly inhabited by Melkite Christians (Greek Catholic).</p>
               
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:QI7EZGJZ">Henri Fleisch’s 1974</rs> <hi rendition="#i">Etudes d’Arabe dialectal</hi> is 
                   a collection of his works on dialectology and includs <hi rendition="#i">Notes sur le dialecte arabe de Zahlé (Liban)</hi>, first 
                   published in MUSJ 27 (1947). 
                   <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:2JQQSW26">Grotzfeld 1978</rs> confirms some of the traits describes by Fleisch for the region, most notably 
                   the pausal diphthongization of unstressed <hi rendition="#i">-ī</hi> and <hi rendition="#i">-ū</hi> in final syllables and lengthening of 
                   the vowel in double closed final syllables but only briefly touches on Zahlé proper. 
                   <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:8GJMIYBF">Wardini’s</rs> article on Lebanon in the EALL offers examples from the Zahlé dialect in 
                   comparison with Northern Beqaa and Beirut dialects; it also states that the above mentioned 
                   traits are not specific to Zahlé but rather typical of the region.</p>
            </div>

            

